# CyberShield AI Backend - Completed Walkthrough

The backend for CyberShield AI has been fully implemented and verified! Let's review what we've built, focusing especially on the explainability layer you requested.

## 1. What Was Built

We successfully established a multi-agent system encompassing all required features, prioritizing modularity and the ability to explain its decisions.

**Core Components implemented:**
- **Orchestrator ([orchestrator.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/agents/orchestrator.py))**: Coordinates parallel execution of detection agents.
- **5 Detection Agents**:
  - [phishing_detector.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/agents/phishing_detector.py) (Google Safe Browsing + Heuristics)
  - [url_scanner.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/agents/url_scanner.py) (VirusTotal + Heuristics)
  - [deepfake_analyzer.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/agents/deepfake_analyzer.py) (Reality Defender API + Local Fallbacks)
  - [prompt_injection.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/agents/prompt_injection.py) (Pattern matching + LLM semantic analysis)
  - [anomaly_detector.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/agents/anomaly_detector.py) (Statistical ML via IsolationForest)
- **Cross-Validator ([cross_validator.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/agents/cross_validator.py))**: Consolidates results to reduce false positives.
- **Explainability Layer ([explainer.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/llm/explainer.py), [breadcrumb_generator.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/services/breadcrumb_generator.py))**: LLM-powered explanations and frontend-ready visual markers.
- **Adversarial Tester ([adversarial_tester.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/services/adversarial_tester.py))**: Mutations to test pipeline robustness (for the 10 bonus marks).

## 2. LLM Explainability & Breadcrumbs in Action

To address your specific question about tracing the reasoning, here is an example of what the API returns. We updated [test_api.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/test_api.py) to highlight this.

When scanning a phishing email, the `POST /api/analyze` endpoint goes beyond just saying "this is phishing." It provides:

### A. The LLM Explanation ([explainer.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/llm/explainer.py))
Triggered by the [explainer.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/llm/explainer.py) agent, powered by Groq (LLaMA-3.3-70B), the API returns a structured JSON object.

```json
"explanation": {
  "summary": "This email is highly suspicious and resembles a classic phishing attack. It attempts to create urgency to steal your login credentials.",
  "reasoning_chain": [
    "The email was flagged by the phishing detector with 86% confidence.",
    "Multiple social engineering urgency keywords were identified.",
    "The email lacks a DKIM signature, meaning the sender cannot be verified."
  ],
  "evidence_citations": [
    "[phishing] No DKIM Signature: Email lacks DKIM signature — cannot verify sender authenticity",
    "[phishing] Social Engineering Patterns: Found 6 urgency/manipulation keywords: immediate, suspend, unauthorized, click here, within 24 hours, security alert"
  ],
  "confidence_justification": "Based on 1 agent detections with cross-validation.",
  "recommended_actions": [
    "Do NOT click any links in this email",
    "Report this email as phishing to your IT department",
    "Verify the sender through an independent channel"
  ]
}
```
**Where is this code?** It lives in [backend/llm/explainer.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/llm/explainer.py). We pipe the detections and context directly into the Groq prompt.

### B. Visual Breadcrumbs ([breadcrumb_generator.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/services/breadcrumb_generator.py))
To make this easy to display on the frontend (e.g., highlighting dangerous text in red), the API returns pre-processed breadcrumb objects.

```json
"breadcrumbs": [
  {
    "id": "abc12345",
    "content_snippet": "...Click here immediately to verify your identity...",
    "threat_type": "phishing",
    "severity": "red",
    "description": "Found 6 urgency/manipulation keywords: immediate, suspend...",
    "position": {"start": 105, "end": 155},
    "highlight_color": "#FF3B30"
  },
  {
    "id": "def67890",
    "content_snippet": "Email lacks DKIM signature — cannot verify sender authenticity",
    "threat_type": "phishing",
    "severity": "orange",
    "description": "Email lacks DKIM signature — cannot verify sender authenticity",
    "position": null,
    "highlight_color": "#FF9500"
  }
]
```
**Where is this code?** It lives in [backend/services/breadcrumb_generator.py](file:///c:/Users/HP/Desktop/IndiaNext_Pixel_Pilots/backend/services/breadcrumb_generator.py). It maps evidence severity to UI hex colors (`severity_colors`).

## 3. How to Test It Yourself

1.  Make sure your local server is running:
    ```bash
    .\venv\Scripts\python.exe -m uvicorn backend.main:app --port 8000
    ```
2.  Run the test script to see the new detailed printouts:
    ```bash
    .\venv\Scripts\python.exe test_api.py
    ```

You will now see exactly how the LLM explains the risk and how the frontend receives the coordinates to highlight the dangerous text.

## 4. Next Steps

With the backend fully functional, the infrastructure is completely ready. The next logical step is to either:
1. Initialize the frontend PWA (e.g., using Next.js/React).
2. Connect the frontend to these API endpoints to render the dashboards and visual breadcrumbs.
